Description: A sealing from a document, impressed from a large gem, with an eagle's head to right, below which are four diminutive busts: apparently a male facing a woman, with a smaller bust behind each, but the sex is not certain in all cases. The back has an impression of the papyrus document to which it was attached, with a hole for the binding string. Micaceous dark grey-brown Nile silt.
Curator's comments: Petrie, Tanis I, 43, Pl. xii (No.12) See Favard-Meeks in Brissaud and Zivie-Coche: Tanis 1987-1997 (1998) p.127.

Terracotta IV Donated: Egypt Exploration Fund. From Find 35 at Tanis: see registration no. 1885,1101.542. The heads on this seal may be Augustus to left, facing Livia to right, with busts of Gaius and Lucius Caesar. Roman, late first century BC. Bibliog: Petrie 1885: 43, pl. xii:12: found with the large quantity of papyrus, of Ptolemaic to Hadrianic date, recovered in the house; Favard-Meeks 1998: 127, and pl. xii:12.
Bibliographic references: Terracotta / Catalogue of Terracottas in the British Museum (3621)
